    "overview": "Lesson 1 opens the sub-strand by presenting students with a striking, concrete contradiction: a beautifully intact pinned butterfly collected a decade ago from Kakamega Forest — still displaying vivid colours and perfect wing venation — placed beside either a photograph or a teacher-described account of a grasshopper caught in the school field, sealed overnight in a plastic bag, and found the next morning black, shrivelled, and emitting a foul odour. A further contrast is introduced with a pressed herbarium leaf mounted on card versus a fresh sukuma wiki leaf left on a desk for a few hours, already wilting and discolouring. These two paired contrasts are the anchoring phenomena for the entire sub-strand. Students are not told the explanation; instead, they are invited to wonder.\n\nIn the Predict and Observe phases, learners draw on everyday knowledge of rotting food — ugali left uncovered, nyama choma left overnight, overripe mangoes in Kisumu market — to hypothesise why organisms decompose and what might stop that process. They record initial models in their notebooks: labelled drawings showing what they think is happening inside the butterfly versus inside the grasshopper. These 'naive models' are explicitly valued as the scientific starting point, not as wrong answers to be replaced.\n\nThe lesson culminates in the creation of the class Driving Question Board (DQB), a central display where student-generated questions are posted and categorised. Students also produce their first annotated model, which they will revise across all 14 lessons of the sub-strand. By the end of this lesson, every learner should be able to state in their own words why the phenomenon is puzzling and articulate at least one specific question they want to investigate — establishing the epistemic foundation for the entire inquiry sequence.",
