        "teacherMoves": "Distribute the observation table (or direct students to draw a 4-column table: Feature | Preserved Butterfly | Rotted Grasshopper | Pressed Herbarium Leaf | Wilting Fresh Leaf). Say: 'You have 5 minutes to fill in this table using only your eyes and the information I give you. Do not write explanations yet — only observations.' Circulate and prompt hesitant students with: 'What do you notice about the colour? What about the shape? Has anything changed from what a living butterfly would look like?' After 5 minutes, read aloud the National Museums of Kenya scenario card in a narrative voice, with emphasis. Then say: 'At the bottom of your table, write exactly two sentences starting with I notice… and two sentences starting with I wonder… You have 3 minutes.' Cold-call 4 students (2 for 'I notice', 2 for 'I wonder') — deliberately select one student who wrote a misconception in the Predict phase to see if observation has shifted their thinking. WAIT TIME: 10 seconds after posing the question before accepting responses. Record all 'I wonder' statements on the board — these will seed the DQB.",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Notice-Wonder Protocol: Separating observation (I notice) from interpretation (I wonder) is a scientific practice that prevents premature explanation. By forcing students to record observations before explanations, the teacher ensures evidence-gathering remains honest and phenomenon-driven. The Kenya Museums scenario grounds the observation in a real institutional context, making specimen preservation feel professionally meaningful rather than academic.",
