        "teacherMoves": "Return to the board where 'I wonder' statements are listed. Say: 'Before we can answer any of these questions, we need shared vocabulary. I am going to give you three definitions — write them exactly as I say them.' Dictate: (1) 'A biological specimen is any organism or part of an organism collected, processed, and stored for scientific study.' (2) 'Decomposition is the breakdown of organic matter by bacteria, fungi, and other agents, resulting in the destruction of the organism's structure.' (3) 'Preservation is the application of physical or chemical methods to prevent or slow decomposition, keeping a specimen usable for scientific study.' After writing, say: 'Look at your observation table. With your partner, decide: which vocabulary term matches what happened to the grasshopper, and which matches the butterfly? You have 60 seconds.' Cold-call 2 pairs. Then say: 'Here is the deeper question — WHY does decomposition happen, and WHY might it be stopped? I am not going to tell you the full answer today. That is what we are going to investigate over the next 13 lessons. But I want you to start building a model of your thinking.' WAIT TIME: 15 seconds after posing the 'why' question. Resist filling the silence. Honour all reasonable contributions by writing them on the board under the heading: 'Our current best thinking.'",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Vocabulary-in-Context (VIC): Introducing the three anchor terms (specimen, decomposition, preservation) only AFTER students have observed the phenomenon ensures that words carry meaning derived from experience, not rote definition. The think-pair-share application task immediately tests whether students can map terms to evidence, not just recite definitions. This reflects the KICD emphasis on learner-centred construction of understanding.",
