        "learnerExperience": "Each student writes their two most burning questions from the lesson on separate sticky notes (or slips of paper if sticky notes are unavailable) — one question about WHY decomposition happens and one question about WHAT biologists do to prevent it. Students post their questions on a designated wall space, and the class collaboratively groups similar questions into clusters with teacher facilitation. The class then reads the official Driving Question together aloud: 'How do biologists collect, process, and preserve specimens so that living organisms can be studied long after they are collected — and what can specimens found in our own school environment reveal about local biodiversity?' Each student copies this into their notebook as the heading of their DQB page, which they will update throughout the sub-strand.",
        "teacherMoves": "Say: 'You have seen something puzzling today. Good scientists do not just shrug — they turn puzzlement into questions they can investigate. Write your two best questions on these slips of paper. Question 1 starts with WHY — why does one specimen survive and the other does not? Question 2 starts with WHAT or HOW — what do biologists actually do, or how do they do it?' Allow 3 minutes of silent writing. Collect and post all questions on the DQB wall display. Read several aloud, then say: 'I see several questions about chemicals — let us group those here. I see questions about equipment — here. Questions about how long preservation lasts — here.' Facilitate grouping in under 2 minutes. Then say together as a class, reading in unison from the board: 'How do biologists collect, process, and preserve specimens so that living organisms can be studied long after they are collected — and what can specimens found in our own school environment reveal about local biodiversity?' Say: 'This is our driving question. Every lesson, we will come back to this board and answer: what have we learned that gets us closer to answering it? Copy it into your notebook now.' WAIT TIME: After posting questions, pause 10 seconds and scan all questions silently before grouping — this models the scientific practice of careful reading before classification.",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Driving Question Board (DQB) as Epistemic Anchor: The DQB externalises and organises the class's collective intellectual agenda. By physically posting questions and clustering them, students see that science proceeds from questions, not answers. The DQB will be revisited at the start of every subsequent lesson, creating a running record of growing understanding. This structure embodies the NGSS Science and Engineering Practice of Asking Questions and Defining Problems.",
