        "teacherMoves": "Say: 'Scientists do not just take notes — they build models. A model is a drawing or diagram that shows your explanation of HOW something works. Your model does not need to be perfect. It needs to show your CURRENT best thinking.' Write on the board: 'Model 1 Requirements: (1) Draw both specimens side by side with labels. (2) Draw arrows showing what you think is happening INSIDE each. (3) Write one or two sentences: My current explanation is…' Allow 5 minutes of silent individual drawing. Circulate and make specific positive comments: 'I see you have drawn bacteria inside the grasshopper — interesting idea. Label that so we remember it.' or 'I see you think something in the preserving process stops air getting in — can you show that with an arrow?' Do NOT correct models. Say at the close: 'Date your model and write: Model 1 — Before Investigation. We will return to this exact drawing at the end of our 14 lessons and you will be amazed at how much your thinking has grown.' Cold-call 2 students to briefly share their model with the class — 20 seconds each. WAIT TIME: After asking 'Who would like to share their model?' wait 8 seconds before cold-calling, to allow voluntary hands.",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Initial Explanatory Model (IEM): Drawing a model before instruction externalises tacit prior knowledge and creates a cognitive baseline. The act of drawing forces students to commit to a mechanism (not just a description), which activates deeper thinking than verbal prediction alone. Labelling the model 'Before Investigation' sets up the explicit revision cycle that is central to the NGSS practice of Developing and Using Models. When students revise their model in Lesson 14, the contrast with Model 1 is a powerful metacognitive moment.",
