    "teacherReflection": "1. During the pinning and pressing practice, did all students physically handle the materials, or did some group members remain passive? How will you ensure full participation in the next hands-on lesson?\n2. Were students able to write a specific, step-referenced explanation of the butterfly-versus-grasshopper phenomenon in the Explain Phase, or did their explanations remain vague? What conceptual gap — if any — do you need to address at the start of Lesson 5?\n3. Did the safety instruction on ethanol and formaldehyde feel fully integrated into the lesson, or did it feel like an interruption? How might you embed safety even more naturally into the hands-on activities in future iterations?\n4. Looking at the students' DQB wonder notes, are the questions they are asking genuinely moving toward chemical preservation (Lesson 5) and long-term storage (Lesson 6), or are they circling back to earlier content? What does this tell you about gaps in the sequence?\n5. Was the 40-minute period sufficient to complete both demonstrations AND both hands-on activities? If not, which activity would you move to Lesson 5 as a starter, and how would that affect the storyline continuity?",
    "summaryTablePrompt": {
      "observed": "Students observed the teacher demonstrate the four-step insect processing workflow (killing, relaxing, spreading/setting, pinning) and the plant pressing procedure (blotting, arranging, layering in newspaper, applying board pressure), and observed safe handling practices for ethanol and formaldehyde in a laboratory context.",
      "learned": "Processing a specimen immediately after collection — through killing, relaxing, spreading, pinning (insects) or blotting and pressing (plants) — removes moisture and stops biological activity, which prevents the microbial decomposition that destroyed the grasshopper in the sealed bag overnight.",
      "explained": "The Kakamega butterfly survived for ten years because it was processed correctly: killed humanely, relaxed, spread with wings in the correct position, pinned through the thorax, and stored dry. The grasshopper in the plastic bag had none of these interventions — it retained moisture, remained in a warm sealed environment, and was rapidly decomposed by microorganisms. Processing is the critical bridge between collection and long-term preservation."
    }
