        "teacherMoves": "Display both anchor images side by side on the board (the pinned Kakamega butterfly and the shrivelled overnight grasshopper). Say: 'Before we touch your project materials, look back at the model you drew in Lesson 1. In your notebook, complete this sentence: Since Lesson 1, I now understand that decomposition is stopped by — blank — because — blank. You have three minutes, working alone.' Set a visible timer. After three minutes say: 'Share your sentence with your partner — 45 seconds.' Then cold-call FOUR students from different teams — deliberately choosing one student whose Lesson 1 model was very simple and one whose earlier work showed strong reasoning. Use exact prompt: 'Tell us your sentence AND one piece of evidence from our lessons that supports it.' Allow 10 seconds WAIT TIME after each response before moving on. Record key vocabulary that emerges (write on the board as a live word-bank for the lesson).",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Activating Prior Knowledge with Sentence Stems — the structured sentence forces students to connect new scientific vocabulary to the specific phenomenon rather than recalling vocabulary in isolation, making misconceptions visible before compilation begins.",
        "formativeAssessment": "Listen for whether students can name a specific mechanism (e.g., 'desiccation removes the water that bacteria need') rather than a vague action ('drying it out keeps it safe'). Students who give only surface-level answers need targeted prompting during the Observe Phase team work. Collect three random notebooks to check sentence quality and flag for follow-up."
