      {
        "phase": "Observe Phase",
        "learnerExperience": "Teams spend 15 minutes at their stations compiling their project portfolio components laid out on the desk: (1) completed field data sheets with locality, date, collector name, habitat notes, and weather; (2) pinned/mounted insect specimens or pressed plant specimens in labelled folders; (3) printed or hand-drawn photographs of released organisms with GPS/locality notes; (4) a draft written report using the provided template headings (Introduction, Methods, Results, Discussion, Conclusion). Each team uses the Project Rubric (distributed by the teacher) to self-assess their portfolio's completeness. After 10 minutes, teams rotate one station to the right and conduct a 5-minute peer review — using the rubric to write two specific compliments and one specific improvement suggestion on a sticky note left on the portfolio.",
        "teacherMoves": "Distribute the Project Rubric and say: 'For the next 10 minutes your team checks your own portfolio against every row of the rubric. Mark each row: green tick if complete, orange dot if partially done, red cross if missing. Be honest — this is your evidence, not just a grade.' Circulate actively, crouching to team level. Use targeted probes: 'Show me your locality label for this specimen — does it include the date AND the habitat description?' and 'Your data sheet says you collected three insects — where are the three specimens?' After 10 minutes signal the rotation: 'Stand up, leave your portfolio on the desk, rotate clockwise to the next team's station. You have five minutes to read their portfolio and leave a sticky note with two specific things they did well and one specific thing to improve — use the rubric row numbers.' After rotation, signal return and allow 2 minutes for teams to read their feedback sticky note aloud within the team.",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Gallery Walk with Structured Peer Critique — teams act as critical reviewers using a shared rubric, which mirrors the peer-review process used by professional biologists submitting to journals; this builds metacognitive awareness of what constitutes complete, credible scientific documentation.",
        "formativeAssessment": "Scan rubric self-assessments for honesty and accuracy — watch for teams that mark everything green without justification. Check that locality labels on specimens include: organism name (common + where known scientific), date, collector, habitat, and collection method. Flag any team with more than two red-cross rows for targeted support during the Explain Phase."
      },
      {
        "phase": "Explain Phase",
        "learnerExperience": "Each team opens their project report to the Discussion section and, using the live word-bank on the board plus their textbook and field notes, writes three to five sentences that directly answer: 'How did the preservation technique we used prevent decomposition in our specimens?' They must reference at least two scientific mechanisms (e.g., ethanol denatures microbial enzymes; pinning plus desiccation removes water needed for bacterial growth; pressing removes moisture and flattens tissue reducing surface area for oxidation). Teams then draft a one-paragraph 'Conclusion' that links their local school biodiversity findings back to the driving question.",
        "teacherMoves": "Write this prompt visibly on the board: 'Our preservation technique stopped decomposition because… [mechanism 1]. It also prevented… [mechanism 2]. Our specimens show that the school environment contains… which tells us about local biodiversity.' Say: 'Use the word-bank, your notes from all seven lessons, and your textbook. You are writing as biologists now — every claim needs a mechanism, not just an action.' Circulate and read over shoulders. Pause at three different teams to ask: 'You wrote that drying stops decay — can you add one sentence explaining WHY drying stops decay at the cellular or microbial level?' Allow 10 seconds WAIT TIME before offering a prompt if the team is stuck. After 8 minutes, cold-call TWO teams to read their Discussion sentences aloud. After each, ask the class: 'Thumbs up if they named a specific mechanism — thumbs sideways if it is still too vague.' Use the class response to guide brief whole-class clarification if needed. Explicitly connect back to the phenomenon: 'This is exactly why Mama Achieng's butterfly from Kakamega Forest looks perfect after ten years — what mechanism kept it intact?'",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Claim-Evidence-Reasoning (CER) Writing — students must move from observation ('we used ethanol') to mechanism ('ethanol denatures the enzymes that drive autolysis') to reasoning ('therefore cell breakdown stops and the specimen is preserved'), mirroring the scientific explanation structure used in peer-reviewed biology.",
        "formativeAssessment": "Read Discussion drafts for presence of two distinct mechanisms. Accept partial credit for mechanism identification (names the process correctly) even if the explanation is incomplete — note these for individual follow-up in Lesson 8. Strong responses will connect mechanism explicitly to a specific decomposition pathway (microbial, enzymatic, oxidative, or moisture-dependent)."
      },
      {
        "phase": "Driving Question Board (DQB) Creation",
        "learnerExperience": "Each team sends one representative to the class Driving Question Board. Teams place a GREEN sticky tag over any question on the board that their project evidence now answers confidently, and write a one-sentence evidence summary on the tag. Teams place a YELLOW tag on questions that are partially answered and a RED tag on questions still unresolved. The whole class then reads the board together, and the teacher facilitates a 3-minute discussion about what Lesson 8 (final presentations) must still address.",
        "teacherMoves": "Hand each team three green, two yellow, and one red sticky tag. Say: 'Walk to the DQB. Your team has collected real evidence across seven lessons. Use green to mark questions your evidence answers — write your evidence in one sentence on the tag. Use yellow for partial answers. Use red for anything still genuinely uncertain.' Allow 3 minutes for teams to tag. Then stand at the DQB and say: 'Let's read the board together. I see the question — How does desiccation prevent decomposition? — has three green tags. What is the consensus answer our class has built?' Cold-call THREE different students (not team representatives) to synthesise answers. Then point to any RED-tagged questions: 'These are honest scientific uncertainties. In Lesson 8 you will have a chance to address them in your presentations. What additional evidence could you cite?' Allow 10 seconds WAIT TIME. Record any RED questions on the board under the heading 'Still to resolve — Lesson 8 presentations'.",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Collaborative Knowledge Mapping on the DQB — colour-coded tagging makes the class's collective epistemic progress visible and distinguishes between settled understanding, partial understanding, and genuine open questions; this mirrors how scientists track the status of claims in a field of inquiry.",
        "formativeAssessment": "Check that green tags contain a genuine evidence sentence (not just 'yes we know this'). The presence of yellow and red tags is healthy and indicates honest metacognition — a class with all green tags may be overconfident. Note which specific questions remain red, as these will structure Lesson 8 Q&A."
      },
      {
        "phase": "Model Building Phase",
        "learnerExperience": "Students return to their individual Lesson 1 model diagrams. Using a different coloured pen or pencil, they revise and annotate the model by: (a) adding arrows labelled with specific mechanisms (e.g., 'pinning + desiccation → removes H₂O → bacteria cannot reproduce → no putrefaction'); (b) crossing out any naive or incorrect labels from Lesson 1 and writing a corrected version beside them; (c) adding a new panel or section to the diagram showing what happens at the cellular/microbial level when preservation succeeds versus when it fails (as in the overnight grasshopper). Teams share revised models within the group and give one peer compliment and one peer challenge before the lesson closes.",
        "teacherMoves": "Say: 'Open to your Lesson 1 model. Pick up a different colour — this colour represents everything you now know. Do not erase anything from Lesson 1 — we want to SEE the change in your thinking. Add arrows, labels, cross-outs, and a new panel showing the microbial or cellular level. You have 6 minutes.' Set timer. Circulate and look for students who are only cosmetically changing their models. Prompt: 'Show me where decomposition actually STARTS in the grasshopper — at the cellular level, what happens first? Now show me which step your preservation technique interrupts.' After 6 minutes: 'Share your revised model with your team. Give one specific compliment — name something your partner now explains correctly that they did not before. Then give one challenge — ask them one question about something they still haven't explained clearly in the model.' Allow 3 minutes for team sharing. Close by cold-calling TWO students to hold up their revised models and narrate one change they made: 'Tell us what you changed and WHY — what evidence made you change it?' Connect explicitly to the phenomenon: 'If Mama Achieng's child had learned this in Form One, what label would they add to explain why the Kakamega butterfly is still perfect today?'",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Model Revision with Visible Thinking — using a contrasting colour to annotate (rather than replacing) the Lesson 1 model makes conceptual growth literally visible on the page; this is a metacognitive tool that helps students and teachers see not just what students now know, but what they changed their minds about and why.",
        "formativeAssessment": "Look for three quality indicators in revised models: (1) at least one mechanism label that goes beyond surface description to cellular/microbial level; (2) a cross-out of at least one naive Lesson 1 idea with a correction; (3) a new panel or section showing the contrast between preserved and unpreserved specimens. Collect four models (one per team) to assess overnight and return with written feedback before Lesson 8 presentations."
      }
