    "teacherReflection": "1. Did every learner's Final Explanation paragraph include at least three of the five required elements (preservation technique, decomposition mechanism, unit evidence, ethical consideration, biodiversity insight)? What patterns in gaps do I see — and what does that tell me about which lessons in the unit were least effective?\n2. During the gallery walk, which team's display was the weakest in connecting their specimen collection to the driving question? What support could I have provided earlier in the unit to strengthen their project work?\n3. How many DQB questions remained on red (unanswered) at the end of the lesson? Are these genuinely open scientific questions, or do they indicate concepts I did not teach deeply enough? How will I address these in Sub-Strand 1.3 or in a future revision of this unit?\n4. When learners compared their Lesson 1 model to their Final Model, did they identify conceptual changes (e.g., understanding why methods work biologically) or only procedural changes (e.g., knowing more steps)? What does this reveal about the depth of understanding achieved?\n5. Were the ethical and environmental responsibilities of specimen collection genuinely discussed — with real disagreement and reasoning — or did learners simply agree with whatever was said first? What discussion moves could I use in future lessons to generate more authentic ethical reasoning about biodiversity and conservation in Kenyan ecosystems like Kakamega Forest?",
