      "explained": "The Kakamega butterfly survived a decade because a biologist used proper dry preservation — it was killed humanely, relaxed, pinned in spread position, dried completely to remove moisture, and stored in a sealed, pest-protected box that eliminated all conditions for decomposition. The grasshopper decomposed overnight because it was sealed in a plastic bag alive or freshly dead — warmth, moisture, and oxygen inside the bag accelerated bacterial and fungal decomposition and enzyme autolysis within hours. The contrast between the two outcomes is entirely explained by whether the conditions for decomposition were removed or maintained."
