      "exemplar": "Dry preservation through pinning and setting is the standard technique for insects and is widely used by entomologists studying Kenya's rich insect biodiversity. After killing, the insect is pinned through the thorax with a stainless-steel entomological pin and mounted on a setting board with wings spread symmetrically. Once dry — typically after one to two weeks depending on humidity — the lack of moisture prevents any microbial growth, since bacteria and fungi cannot reproduce without liquid water. This is the method used for the Kakamega Forest butterfly in our anchoring phenomenon, and it is effective for decades when combined with fumigant storage.\n\nWet preservation in fixatives such as formaldehyde (formalin) solution or 70% ethanol is used for soft-bodied organisms that would shrink or distort if dried. Fish specimens from Lake Victoria, frogs from Kenyan wetlands, earthworms, and dissected organs are all preserved this way. Formaldehyde works by cross-linking proteins — it forms chemical bonds between amino acid chains, denaturing enzymes and physically locking cell structures in place so that autolysis cannot proceed. Ethanol preserves by dehydrating tissues and denaturing proteins simultaneously. Both chemicals kill microorganisms present in the tissue.\n\nHerbarium pressing is used for plant specimens. Plants such as the Nandi flame tree (Spathodea campanulata) or common sukuma wiki (Kale, Brassica oleracea) can be pressed between sheets of newspaper inside a wooden plant press, with the press tightened using bolts to apply even pressure. The newspaper absorbs moisture rapidly, and the pressed, dried plant is then mounted on acid-free card and labelled. Drying halts both enzymatic decomposition and fungal attack. Herbarium sheets at institutions like the East African Herbarium in Nairobi remain identifiable after more than a century.\n\nFreeze-drying (lyophilisation) is a more advanced preservation technique used in research institutions. The specimen is first frozen and then placed in a vacuum chamber where ice sublimes directly to water vapour without passing through a liquid phase. This removes almost all moisture while maintaining the three-dimensional structure of the specimen — important for displaying mammals or birds in natural history museums. The National Museums of Kenya uses this technique for some of its large mammal displays. Finally, glycerine preservation is used for delicate plant organs and embryos: the specimen is soaked in glycerine, which replaces cellular water with the viscous alcohol, preventing collapse of soft tissues and keeping specimens pliable and transparent for long-term microscopic study."
