      "exemplar": "Claim: The specimen collection conducted across our school grounds reveals that even a small, semi-urban environment supports meaningful biodiversity across multiple taxonomic groups, though this diversity is likely an underestimate of the true local species richness.\n\nEvidence from our class collection showed that within the school compound — sampling habitats including the grass field, the kitchen garden, the drainage ditch, and the base of the perimeter trees — we identified at least fourteen distinct insect species (including three butterfly species, two grasshopper species, one praying mantis, two beetle species, and several ant and fly species), four plant species not previously catalogued in the school garden, and two species of soil invertebrates recovered by pitfall traps set near the compost pit. This diversity across three major taxonomic groups (Insecta, Plantae, and other invertebrates) demonstrates that even a school environment modified by human activity retains ecological complexity, likely sustained by the presence of flowering plants, decomposing organic matter in the compost area, and the margin habitats along the school fence line.\n\nThe reasoning connecting this evidence to biodiversity conclusions is straightforward: the presence of multiple trophic levels — producers (plants), primary consumers (herbivorous insects), and decomposers (soil invertebrates and bacteria evidenced by decomposing leaf litter) — indicates a functioning local ecosystem with energy flow and nutrient cycling. However, a significant limitation of our collection is collection effort bias: we sampled for only two lesson periods and restricted our area to the school compound. Many species, particularly nocturnal insects, burrowing soil organisms, and migratory birds that pass through the area, would not have been detected by our methods. Our sweep nets and pitfall traps are also biased toward certain body sizes and activity patterns. A full biodiversity survey would require repeated sampling across seasons using multiple methods, as professional surveys conducted by the National Museums of Kenya typically do when establishing species inventories for a new site."
