      "exemplar": "During this unit, the scientific practice I developed most significantly was planning and carrying out investigations. At the start, when asked to plan how we would sample insects from three different school microhabitats, my group's first plan was simply to 'walk around and catch whatever we see.' After feedback from our teacher and examining the investigation planning framework on the Driving Question Board, I realised that a valid comparison between habitats requires standardised effort — the same amount of time, the same tools, and the same number of sweeps in each location. We redesigned our plan to use ten sweep net passes per microhabitat, timed at five minutes each, with two collectors working simultaneously. This change made our data comparable across sites and gave us results we could actually use to make claims about which microhabitat supported the greatest insect diversity.\n\nOne significant challenge we encountered was during the pinning stage of our insect specimens. Two of our grasshoppers had been left in the killing jar for too long before we could process them, and by the time we attempted to pin them their legs had already stiffened in unnatural positions and one abdomen had begun to show signs of early decomposition (a faint unpleasant odour and slight discolouration). We learned that insects must be processed quickly after killing — ideally within 24 hours — or stored in a relaxing box (a sealed container with a damp cloth to restore pliability) before setting. This mistake taught me that timing and workflow planning are as important in specimen preparation as having the correct equipment.\n\nAccurate labelling and documentation are scientifically essential because a specimen without data is scientifically worthless, regardless of how perfectly it is preserved. A beautifully pinned butterfly with no label telling us where, when, and by whom it was collected cannot contribute to studies of species distribution, seasonal abundance, or changes in biodiversity over time. The great natural history collections of the world — including those at the National Museums of Kenya — are scientifically valuable precisely because each specimen carries a data label recording locality, date, collector, and habitat. When researchers today study how climate change is shifting insect ranges across East Africa, they rely on comparing current observations with data recorded on specimens collected decades ago. Without that documentation, the comparison is impossible. A specimen is, in essence, a data point — and like any data point, it is only meaningful when its context is recorded."
